            <br />
            <h4><strong> - <u>What is energy?</u></strong></h4>
                <br />
                <p>
                    Energy is a difficult thing to define but physicists often explain it as the ‘capacity to do
                    <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration: underline;" title="Work" data-container="body" data-toggle="popover" data-placement="top"
                       data-content="A technical way of saying energy is transferred from one place to another."
                       data-original-title="Work" aria-describedby="popover168466">work</a>’.
                </p>
                <p>
                    For example, a person throwing a ball would need to do work by moving their arms and body; the energy is transferred from the person to the ball.
                    The person can then stand still while the ball continues to travel because of the energy the ball still retains.
                </p>
                <div class="row justify-content-center">
                    <div class="card text-white bg-dark mb-3">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                                <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson1/mobilechallenge-active-athlete-2554114.jpg" alt="Photo of a volleyball player" class="responsive" />
                                <figcaption>Photo by Mateusz Dach from Pexels</figcaption>
                            </figure>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p>
                    Energy is also used when discussing the
                    <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration: underline;" title="Temperature" data-container="body" data-toggle="popover" data-placement="top"
                       data-content="Temperature is actually a way of saying the amount of energy something contains." data-original-title="Temperature"
                       aria-describedby="popover168466">temperature</a> of an object. In general
                    terms, something with a higher temperature has more energy than something with
                    a lower temperature (fridges and freezers are exceptions to the rule).
                </p>
                <div class="row justify-content-center">
                    <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                                <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson1/barbecue-bbq-briquettes-9263.jpg" alt="Glowing barbeque coals" class="responsive" />
                                <figcaption>Photo by Skitterphoto from Pexels</figcaption>
                            </figure>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p>
                    A fire is a source of large amounts of energy, usually given off as heat and light.
                    Sometimes, there is so much energy in an object that it '
                    <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration: underline;" title="Radiation" data-container="body" data-toggle="popover" data-placement="top"
                       data-content="Energy is released in the form of an electromagnetic wave in visible (light) and invisible (infra-red, ultraviolet) ranges."
                       data-original-title="Radiation" aria-describedby="popover168466">radiates</a>
                    ' energy in the form of light, hence why barbecue coals glow red.
                </p>
