            <br />
            <h4><strong> - <u>Where does energy come from?</u></strong></h4>

            <br />
            <p>
                Good question! <u>Energy cannot be created or destroyed</u>. It moves from one
                form of energy to another.
            </p>
            <p>
                The principle thing to take away is that the energy we use is not made by us.
                It must have already existed from somewhere, and we are just changing it from one form
                to another that is useful to us.
            </p>
            <p>
                <a href="#" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration: underline;" title="Open question 2" data-container="body" data-toggle="popover" data-placement="top"
                   data-content="The overwhelming theory surrounding the ‘creation’ of all energy is 
                   the ‘big bang’ - the event that started the construction and expansion of the universe.
                   After the big bang, all the energy that was available has been used to create
                   stars, planets and other objects in the cosmos." data-original-title="Work"
                   aria-describedby="popover168466">Can you think of where all the energy might have come from?</a>
            </p>
            <p>
                Life on Earth started by using this energy.
            </p>

            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                            <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson1/beautiful-cropland-dawn-1237119.jpg" class="responsive" />
                            <figcaption>Photo by Jonathan Petersson from Pexels</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>
                Plants
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration: underline;" title="Photosynthesis" data-container="body" data-toggle="popover" data-placement="top"
                   data-content="A process where plants convert energy from sunlight into chemical energy
                   in the form of useable sugars." data-original-title="Photosynthesis" aria-describedby="popover168466">
                    photosynthesise
                </a>
                energy from the sun to make sugars. Without plants exploiting the
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration: underline;" title="Sunlight" data-container="body" data-toggle="popover" data-placement="top"
                   data-content="Currently we use fossil fuels as an energy source. Fossil fuels used to be life that relied on photosynthetic organisms,
                   and the sun's energy. In some respects, we are therefore still using energy from the sun,
                   but it's been converted into different forms of energy." data-original-title="Sunlight" aria-describedby="popover168466">
                    energy from the sun
                </a>, a lot of life would not be here on Earth.
            </p>
            <p>
                On our planet, all energy can be traced back to the Sun, and the Sun’s energy can be
                traced back to the big bang.
            </p>
